The Whatâ€™s

Letâ€™s start with what we have in our hands here and what we may talk about in the article. Itâ€™s good to be ready with the definitions so that you donâ€™t have to run around looking for them.

What is a Markov Chain?

In simple terms (for non-math people):

Itâ€™s a set of observations over time where the current observation depends only on what was observed last â€” not on any earlier observations.

A more mathematical definition would be:

A sequence of random variables having the Markov Property is said to be a Markov Chain (or Process).

The Markov Property is:

\[ P(X_{n+1} = j \mid X_n = i, X_{n-1} = i_{n-1}, \dots, X_0 = i_0) = P(X_{n+1} = j \mid X_n = i) \]

for all \(n \geq 0\) and all states \(i_0, i_1, \dots, i, j\) in the state space.

This property signifies memorylessness.

Wish food options were actually these, but still a worthy example.

Generalising a Bitâ€¦

A standard Markov Chain is of order 1, meaning the future state depends only on the immediate past state.

A Markov Chain of order ( m ) where \(m \geq 1\) is a sequence of random variables \(X_n\) where the future state depends on the $ m $ previous states:

\[ P(X_{n+1} \mid X_n, X_{n-1}, \dots, X_0) = P(X_{n+1} \mid X_n, X_{n-1}, \dots, X_{n-m+1}) \]

In the context of language modeling, this means predicting the next word depends on the ( \(m\) ) preceding words â€” an m-gram model.

The complexity of modeling increases exponentially with ( \(m\) ) due to the size of the transition probability matrix.

A Little About Neural Networks

A Neural Network (NN) is a computational model inspired by the structure and function of biological neural networks.

It is composed of a collection of interconnected nodes (neurons or units) organized in layers â€” input, hidden, and output.

The basic math for Neural Networks is pretty simple â€” Iâ€™d recommend checking out this article by 3b1b

Recurrent Neural Networks (RNN) and Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM)

Neural Networks, in their basic form (like Feed-Forward Networks), treat each input independently. This is insufficient for sequence data like text, where context matters.

RNNs are a class of neural networks where connections between nodes form a directed graph along a temporal sequence. They have an internal loop (or recurrent connection) that allows information from previous steps to persist.

This â€œmemoryâ€ makes them suitable for tasks like sequence prediction and natural language processing.

One of the best discussions on RNNs is in a blog post by Andrej Karpathy â€” definitely worth reading if you want to know more.

LSTMs (Long Short-Term Memory) are a special type of RNN designed to overcome the vanishing gradient problem. They introduce a more complex internal structure called a cell, which can maintain information over long periods.

LSTMs are still pretty useful â€” although they came out long ago, they still do a decent job in forecasting time-series data. To know more about LSTMs, this is my go-to article â€” do read it.

The Idea

As can be seen â€” from Markov Chains to LLMs, all of them have sequential predicting or generating capabilities.

Specifically, text generation is a very interesting aspect of this, and the article will primarily focus on this â€” drawing some parallels between different models and Markov Chains.

N-Gram Language Model

A language model is a machine learning model that predicts upcoming words. More formally, a language model assigns a probability to each possible next word, or equivalently gives a probability distribution over possible next words. Language models can also assign a probability to an entire sentence. Thus an LM could tell us that the following sequence has a much higher probability of appearing in a text:

all of a sudden I notice three guys standing on the sidewalk

than does this same set of words in a different order:

on guys all I of notice sidewalk three a sudden standing th

The simplest kind of language model: the n-gram language model. An n-gram is a sequence of n words: a 2-gram (which weâ€™ll call bigram) is a two-word sequence of words like The water, or water of, and a 3-gram (a trigram) is a three-word sequence of words like The water of, or water of Walden. But here we specifically (in a bit of terminological ambiguity) use the word â€˜n-gramâ€™ to mean a probabilistic model that can estimate the probability of a word given the n-1 previous words, and thereby also to assign probabilities to entire sequences.

Modeling

As we defined earlier we wish to find a model of \(P(w \vert h )\) where \(w\) is some word and \(h\) is the history prior to the word, that is we wish to find the probability of observing a certain word given the prior history.

i.e Assume our history \(h\) is..

â€ The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy â€¦â€

and assume we wish to find the probability of the next word being â€œdogâ€.

One way to estimate this probability is directly from relative frequency counts: take a very large corpus, count the number of times we see The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy , and count the number of times this is followed by dog. This would be answering the question â€œOut of the times we saw the history h, how many times was it followed by the word \(w\), as follows :

\[ P(\text{dog}|\text{The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy})=\frac{C(\text{The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog})}{C(\text{The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy})} \]

If we had a large enough corpus we could compute these probabilities , but even the entire internet filled with books isnâ€™t big enough to give a good estimate of counts for such, and itâ€™s simply because of the fascinating fact that language is creative , new sentences, words are created every then and now.This means there is a non zero probability of the word â€œskibidiâ€ or â€œrizzâ€ appearing at the end of the sentence(Bad Example,but had to do it). We need a more â€œsmarterâ€ way to estimate this probability,that is where Mr.Markov and his genius enters.

The Markov Assumption

The intuition of the n-gram model is that instead of computing the probability of a word given its entire history, we can approximate the history by just the last few words. The bigram model, for example, approximates the probability of a word given bigram all the previous words \(P(w_n|w_{1:nâˆ’1})\) by using only the conditional probability given the preceding word \(P(w_n|w_{nâˆ’1})\). In other words, instead of computing the probabil- ity \[P(\text{dog}|\text{The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy}) \] we approximate it with the probability \[P(\text{dog}|\text{lazy})\] When we use a bigram model to predict the conditional probability of the next word, we are thus making the following approximation: \[P(w_n|w_{1:nâˆ’1}) â‰ˆ P(w_n|w_{nâˆ’1}) \] This seems familiar right?(Given you followed through) This is the Markov Property as we defined earlier.And thus using the Markov Assumption we have a smarter way to predict the probability of some future unit without looking too far into the

The Implementation is quite simple and can be followed through this R code below, which implements a trigram model based on a second order markov assumption.

txt_path <- "tiny_shakespeare.txt"
raw_text <- readLines(txt_path, warn = FALSE)
tokens <- unlist(strsplit(paste(raw_text, collapse = " "), "\\s+"))
tokens <- tokens[tokens != ""]

clean_word <- function(w) {
  w2 <- gsub("[-,.:'?;!]+", "", w)
  tolower(trimws(w2))
}

unigrams <- list()
bigrams  <- list()

n_tokens <- length(tokens)

for (idx in seq(3, n_tokens, by = 2)) {
  unigram_key <- clean_word(tokens[idx - 1])
  next_word    <- clean_word(tokens[idx])

  if (nzchar(unigram_key)) {
    if (is.null(unigrams[[unigram_key]])) {
      unigrams[[unigram_key]] <- next_word
    } else {
      unigrams[[unigram_key]] <- c(unigrams[[unigram_key]], next_word)
    }
  }

  w1 <- clean_word(tokens[idx - 2])
  w2 <- clean_word(tokens[idx - 1])
  big_key <- paste(w1, w2, sep = "||")

  if (nzchar(w1) && nzchar(w2)) {
    if (is.null(bigrams[[big_key]])) {
      bigrams[[big_key]] <- next_word
    } else {
      bigrams[[big_key]] <- c(bigrams[[big_key]], next_word)
    }
  }
}

n <- 20
big_keys <- names(bigrams)
start_big <- sample(big_keys, 1)
parts <- strsplit(start_big, "\\|\\|")[[1]]
start_succ <- sample(bigrams[[start_big]], 1)
text_words <- c(parts[1], parts[2], start_succ)

cat("text:", paste(text_words, collapse = " "))

for (i in seq_len(n)) {
  L <- length(text_words)
  prev_unigram <- text_words[L]
  prev_bigram_key <- paste(text_words[L-1], text_words[L], sep = "||")

  if (!is.null(bigrams[[prev_bigram_key]])) {
    word <- sample(bigrams[[prev_bigram_key]], 1)
  } else if (!is.null(unigrams[[prev_unigram]])) {
    word <- sample(unigrams[[prev_unigram]], 1)
  } else {
    cat("\n")
    break
  }

  cat(" ", word, sep = "")
  text_words <- c(text_words, word)
}
cat("\n")

The code may look a bit complicated but all it does is , removes all the whitespace and puncutations from the text â€“> then turns them into tokens which are just another name for each wordâ€“>At each step the code inspects the most recent context (the last two words) â€“> if there are observed successors for the last two-word pair (i.e.Â bigrams[[prev_bigram_key]] exists), sample uniformly from that successor listâ€“>if no bigram matches, but there is a successor list for the last single word, sample from unigrams[[prev_unigram]]â€“>If neither context has any recorded successors, stop generationâ€“>Each sampled word is appended to text_words, and the loop repeats

The section that enforces the Markov assumption is the decision logic in the generation loop:

if (!is.null(bigrams[[prev_bigram_key]])) {
  word <- sample(bigrams[[prev_bigram_key]], 1)
} else if (!is.null(unigrams[[prev_unigram]])) {
  word <- sample(unigrams[[prev_unigram]], 1)
}

This says: the probability distribution for the next token w_t depends only on the last 2 tokens (the bigram key) â€” that is a second-order Markov model (order = 2). If that 2-token context is not available, it falls back to a first-order model (depends only on the last token).

RNNâ€™S , LSTMâ€™s and where Markov Chains Stand

Although thereâ€™s no direct theoretical relations between Recurrent Neural Networks their successor LSTMâ€™s and Markov Chains.I felt the article would be incomplete if a section on them was not written, since i am extensively writing on Language Models.

Fundamentally, both approaches share a singular objective: modeling the conditional probability distribution of a sequence. While the mathematical substrates differâ€”one relies on discrete probability tables, the other on continuous vector space transformationsâ€”they both operate under the assumption that the future state is contingent upon the current context.

The primary distinction lies in how that context is encoded and retained.In a classical Markov model, memory is explicitly finite and discrete. An \(n\)-order chain considers only the immediately preceding \(n\) observations, effectively discarding all prior history. This creates a rigid â€œhorizonâ€ of context; the model cannot account for dependencies that span beyond this fixed window. It treats language as a series of local, probable transitions rather than a cohesive narrative.

LSTMs circumvent this limitation by replacing the static transition matrix with a dynamic hidden state. Rather than looking up a probability in a table, the network learns a function to approximate it. Through its internal gating mechanismsâ€”specifically the forget, input, and output gatesâ€”an LSTM selectively preserves or discards information over arbitrary time steps. This allows the model to maintain a persistent representation of relevant features, such as the subject of a sentence, across gaps that would render a Markov chain incoherent. Consequently, the LSTM can be viewed as an attempt to approximate a Markov process with an infinitely variable memory window, managed through learned parameters rather than hard-coded rules.

Atleast for basic text generation like tasks, vanilla RNN doesnâ€™t differ much from markov chain based language models as can be seen from this piece of text, which includes text generated from Markov Chain based Trigram and a vanilla RNN trained on the same text.

LLMâ€™s as Markov Chain

In this section we try to understand the theoretical standpoint of how Large Language Modelâ€™s can be expressed as an equivalent finite state Markov Chain,

Prior to this , Iâ€™ve already given some formal background on what Markov Chains and LLMâ€™s are.

Mathematical Definitions

Markov chains.

Consider a finite discrete set \(\mathcal{X}\) with cardinality \(|\mathcal{X}|\). We define a discrete-time, time-homogeneous Markov chain, denoted by \(\text{MC}(\mathcal{X}, \mathbf{Q})\), over the state space \(\mathcal{X} = \{x_i\}_{i=1}^{|\mathcal{X}|}\). The dynamics are governed by a transition matrix \(\mathbf{Q} \in \mathbb{R}^{|\mathcal{X}| \times |\mathcal{X}|}\) containing entries \(\mathbf{Q}_{ij} = \mathbf{Q}(x_i, x_j) \in [0, 1]\). This chain consists of a sequence of random variables \(\mathbf{X}\) in \(\mathcal{X}\) satisfying the Markov property; specifically, for any \(n \in \mathbb{N}\) and sequence \((x_1, \ldots, x_{n+1}) \in \mathcal{X}^{n+1}\), the transition probabilities are given by:

\[ \begin{split} &\mathbb{P}(\mathbf{X}_{n+1} = x_{n+1} \mid \mathbf{X}_n = x_n, \ldots, \mathbf{X}_1 = x_1) \\ &\qquad = \mathbb{P}(\mathbf{X}_{n+1} = x_{n+1} \mid \mathbf{X}_n = x_n) \\ &\qquad := \mathbf{Q}(x_n,x_{n+1}). \end{split} \]

A distribution \(\pi\) on \(\mathcal{X}\) is termed stationary if it satisfies the condition \(\pi \mathbf{Q}= \pi\). Convergence of \(\text{MC}(\mathcal{X}, \mathbf{Q})\) to \(\pi\) for a starting state \(x \in \mathcal{X}\) occurs if \(\lim_{n \to \infty} \text{TV}(\mathbf{Q}^n(x, \cdot), \pi) = 0\). Here, \(\mathbf{Q}^n(x, \cdot)\) represents the distribution of \(\mathbf{X}_n\) conditioned on \(\mathbf{X}_1 = x\), and the total variation distance between two distributions \(\mathbb{P}\) and \(\mathbb{Q}\) on a measurable space \((\Omega, \mathcal{F})\) is defined as \(\text{TV}(\mathbb{P}, \mathbb{Q}) := \sup_{A \in \mathcal{F}} | \mathbb{P}(A) - \mathbb{Q}(A) |.\) The convergence rate is characterized by the mixing time \(t_\text{mix}(\varepsilon)\), which is the minimum steps required to reach \(\varepsilon\)-proximity to the stationary distribution. Intuitively, slow mixing implies the chain remains localized near its initial state for an extended period, whereas rapid mixing indicates a swift loss of dependence on the initial condition.

Large language models.

We define a vocabulary \(\mathcal{V}\) of size \(V\) as the dictionary used to encode arbitrary sequences into discrete tokens. The model is constrained by a context window \(T\), limiting the input length. Consequently, the domain of a transformer-based autoregressive LLM is the space of all token sequences with length at most \(T\), denoted by \(\mathcal{V}_T^* := \{ v \in \mathcal{V}^*,\, |v|\leq T\}\), where \(|v|\) represents the length of \(v\). An LLM is formally defined as a parameterized function \(f_{\theta}: \mathcal{V}_T^* \rightarrow \Delta(\mathcal{V})\), with parameters \(\theta\), mapping a sequence \(v\) to a probability distribution over \(\mathcal{V}\) (the probability simplex \(\Delta(\mathcal{V})\)). This output represents the likelihood of the next token given the history \(v\). For notational brevity, we omit the superscripts, referring to the model simply as \(f_{\theta}\). The learnerâ€™s objective is to approximate the true sequence probability distribution \(\mathbb{P}_{\mathcal{L}}: \mathcal{P}(\mathcal{V}_T^*) \rightarrow [0,1]\). Furthermore, we adopt the standard assumption that there exists a constant \(c_0 > 0\) such that for any \(n \in [N]\) and sequence \((x_1, \ldots, x_{n+1}) \in \mathcal{X}^{n+1}\):

\[ \mathbb{P}(\mathbf{X}_{n+1}=x_{n+1} \mid \mathbf{X}_n = x_n, \ldots, \mathbf{X}_1=x_1) \geq c_0. \]

Transformer model.

We assume \(f_{\theta}\) follows a transformer architecture comprising \(L\) layers and \(H\) heads, structured with alternating multi-head attention (MHA) and feed-forward blocks. The processing begins with an input \(\mathbf{S}^{(0)} = \mathbf{S}\) embedded in \(\mathbb{R}^{d}\). To generate the vocabulary distribution, the final layer output \(\mathbf{S}^{(L)} \in \mathbb{R}^{d \times n}\) undergoes projection via an â€œunembedding layerâ€ \(\mathbf{W}_U \in \mathbb{R}^{V \times d}\), followed by column-wise averaging to yield a vector in \(\mathbb{R}^{V}\). The final next-token probability distribution is obtained via a softmax operation:

\[ \mathbb{P}_{\theta}(\cdot \mid \mathbf{S}) := \mathrm{softmax}\left( \frac{1}{n \tau}\mathbf{W}_U \mathbf{S}^{(L)} \mathbf{1}_n\right) \in \Delta_{V} \]

Here, \(\theta\) represents the full parameter set, \(\mathbf{1}_n\) is a vector of ones of size \(n\), and \(\tau\) denotes the softmax temperature. Assuming the unembedding layer is bounded by a constant \(B_U\), we define the feasible parameter space as \(\Theta = \{ \theta \text{ s.t. } \lVert \mathbf{W}_U^\top \rVert_{2, 1} \leq B_U\}\) and the corresponding function class as \(\mathcal{F} = \{ f_{\theta} \text{ s.t. } \theta \in \Theta \}\)

Large Language Models as Markov Chains

We formally define a Markov chain to capture the inference dynamics of an LLM \(f_{\theta}\). We associate a tokenized input sequence with a state \(v_i\), where a transition to a new state \(v_j=[v_i,v]\) occurs by concatenating a predicted token \(v\). This framework applies to any model with a finite vocabulary and fixed context window, including deep transformer-based LLMs.

A small note, here temperature is to be thought of as error, i didnâ€™t change the terminology from the paper to keep things consistent.

Markov Chain Formalization

First, we define sequence compatibility in the context of autoregressive prediction.

Definition (Incompatible Sequences). Let \(u, v \in \mathcal{V}_T^*\) be two sequences of at most \(T\) tokens. We define \(v\) as incompatible with \(u\) if \(v\) cannot physically be a completion of \(u\) due to a mismatch in history:

\[ \exists l\in \{1, \ldots, |u|-1\}, \text{s.t. }(u)_{l+1} \neq (v)_l. \]

We denote the set of incompatible pairs as \(\mathcal{I}\). Accordingly, we define the transition matrix associated with the LLM.

Proposition 1 (Markov Representation). Any large language model \(f_{\theta}\) is equivalent to a Markov chain \(\text{MC}(\mathcal{V}_T^*, \mathbf{Q})\) with a sparse transition matrix \(\mathbf{Q} \in \mathbb{R}^{|\mathcal{V}_T^*|\times |\mathcal{V}_T^*|}\) defined for any \(v_i,v_j \in \mathcal{V}_T^*\) as:

\[ \mathbf{Q}(v_i, v_j) = \begin{cases} 0, & \text{if } (v_i, v_j) \in \mathcal{I} \\ \{f_{\theta}(v_i)\}_{\text{last}}, & \text{otherwise}, \end{cases} \]

where \(\{\cdot\}_{\text{last}}\) denotes the probability assigned to the last token of \(v_j\). Proposition 1 implies that probability mass is only assigned to transitions between compatible sequences.

Properties and Convergence

We characterize the long-term behavior of this chain through the following propositions.

Proposition 2 (Ergodicity). The Markov chain \(\text{MC}(\mathcal{V}_T^*, \mathbf{Q})\) defined in Proposition 1 is ergodic and admits a unique stationary distribution.

This implies the chain consists of a single recurrent class (sequences of maximum length \(T\)) and transient states (shorter sequences). We quantify the convergence rate to this equilibrium below.

Proposition 3 (Stationary Distribution). Let \(\mathbf{e} = (1, \dots , 1)^\top\). As \(n \to \infty\), \(\mathbf{Q}^n\) converges to \(\mathbf{e}{\pi}\), where \({\pi}\) is the stationary distribution. For all \(n \geq T\):

\[ \lvert (\mathbf{Q}^n)_{i,j} - (\mathbf{e}{\pi})_{i,j} \rvert \leq (1-2\varepsilon)^{\lfloor\frac{n}{T}\rfloor - 1}, \]

where \(\varepsilon > 0\) is the minimum transition probability within the recurrent class.

Implications for LLMs

The theoretical framework yields two practical insights:

  1. Looping: The stationary distribution is independent of the initial prompt. Consequently, reaching stationarity implies the model enters a deterministic loop, a known failure mode in LLMs that often necessitates repetition penalties.
  2. Temperature and Coherence: The softmax temperature \(\tau\) directly influences \(\varepsilon\). Increasing \(\tau\) raises the minimum transition probabilities, thereby increasing \(\varepsilon\) and accelerating convergence to the stationary distribution. This theoretically explains why higher temperatures degrade long-term coherence.

What this Meansâ€¦

So, letâ€™s break down whatâ€™s actually happening under the hood here. Think of an LLM like a giant, really complex game of dominoes or a chain link fence. The model is constantly looking at the last chunk of words it wrote to decide what comes next, but it canâ€™t just jump to anywhere it wants. Thereâ€™s a strict rule of compatibility where the end of the last sentence has to perfectly overlap with the start of the next piece. If the history doesnâ€™t match up physicallyâ€”like trying to connect â€œThe cat satâ€ directly to â€œalgebra is hardâ€â€”the model sees that move as impossible. Itâ€™s strictly locked into paths where the words flow logically from the immediate context.

So now the whole system can be explained through a Markov Chain, which is quite amazing since now we can explain the whole thing through definite probabilities. Imagine a massive map where the AI is hopping from one phrase to another. Because of that matching rule we just talked about, most paths on this map are blocked off, so the AI is funneled down specific routes.

Here is where it gets kind of trippy though. If you let the model keep generating text forever, it essentially develops amnesia. Thereâ€™s this concept called a stationary distribution, which is a mathematical way of saying that eventually, the model stops caring about that original prompt you gave it and settles into a sort of â€œdefault mode.â€ It forgets where it started and just drifts into a stable, often repetitive state.

That actually explains two big things youâ€™ve probably noticed when using these tools. First, you know how sometimes a bot will glitch out and just start repeating the same phrase over and over again? Thatâ€™s not really a bug; itâ€™s actually the model reaching that stable â€œdefaultâ€ state we just talked about. It gets stuck in a loop because thatâ€™s the mathematical path of least resistance. Second, if you crank up the â€œtemperatureâ€ setting to make the AI more creative, youâ€™re basically telling it to take riskier jumps between states. While that sounds cool, it actually makes the model reach that repetitive loop state faster. By jumping around more randomly, it forgets your instructions sooner and loses the plot, drifting into gibberish or loops way quicker than if you had kept it on a tighter leash.
